    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-10T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-10T12:00:00-05:00" n="963"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d963">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 EW/11–1044: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Ireland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gray</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dublin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-10T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >November 10, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 11—4:12 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>196. On November 9 in Dail Mr. De Valera was urged to reply to questions
                    regarding Irish answer to American request for denial of asylum to Axis war
                    criminals. He refused to reply pleading reasons of state and suggested that he
                    was not free to give text of his answer without the consent of others, implying
                    that we did not wish publication. It is probable that the true reason for his
                    embarrassed reticence was that he did not wish to disclose our dissatisfaction
                    with his reply.</p>
                <p>Some Cabinet members are spreading report that we are satisfied with reply. I
                    have corrected this impression in confidence when appropriate <pb facs="1462"
                        n="1448" xml:id="pg_1448"/> occasion offered. It is probably advisable to
                    let Irish Government suppress the facts till it suits your convenience to make
                    announcement. But you might instruct me to notify De Valera that we had no wish
                    to cause him embarrassment and that he was at liberty to publish the full record
                    at his convenience.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gray</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
